                        "": [
                            {
                                "def": "the act of speaking alone or to oneself, esp as a theatrical device",
                                "mark": "good"
                            },
                            {
                                "def": "a speech in a play that is spoken in soliloquy",
                                "example": "Hamlet's first soliloquy",
                                "mark": "good"
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "forms": {
                        "info": "",
                        "items": []
                    },
                    "value": "noun"
                }
            ],
            "note": "Soliloquy is sometimes wrongly used where monologue is meant. Both words refer to a long speech by one person, but a monologue can be addressed to other people, whereas in a soliloquy the speaker is always talking to himself or herself",
            "origin": "C17: via Late Latin sōliloquium, from Latin sōlus sole + loquī to speak",
            "word": "soliloquy"
        }
    ],
    "examples": [
        "He composed his face as if to deliver Hamlet's saddest soliloquy.",
        "soliloquy might have succeeded in doing just that if he hadn't been in love and overflowing with a marvellous sense of aliveness.",
        "Steil wondered if the Lexus woman had been more surprised by the perforations than by his soliloquy."
    ],
    "translations": []
